        <h2>Time it right</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Travel off-season and midweek.</strong> The same destination can be 30–50% cheaper a week outside school holidays, and Tuesday/Wednesday flights beat weekend ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Book flights early, lodging late.</strong> Airfare tends to climb as the date nears; hotel and rental prices often drop as owners fill empty nights.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a school break that isn't the obvious one.</strong> A long weekend in October is a fraction of spring break.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Make points work for one income</h2>
        <p>You don't need to be a "points person" to benefit. One travel rewards card, used for the spending you already do (groceries, gas, bills), can cover a flight a year.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Put recurring expenses on one rewards card and pay it off monthly.</strong> The points add up without changing your spending.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch for sign-up bonuses</strong> — a single bonus can be worth a domestic round-trip.</li>
          <li><strong>Hotel and airline loyalty programs are free</strong> — join them even if you only travel once a year. See <a href="{{ '/financial/budgeting/' | url }}">Budgeting on One Income</a> to keep the card from becoming a debt trap.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Cut the on-the-ground costs</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Rent a place with a kitchen.</strong> Eating breakfast and a few dinners "at home" is the biggest saving on any trip — a <a href="{{ '/go/vrbo' | url }}" rel="sponsored nofollow">whole-home rental</a> pays for itself in food.</li>
          <li><strong>Pack a day bag of snacks and water.</strong> Theme-park and airport prices are brutal; a backpack of your own saves real money daily.</li>
          <li><strong>Look for "kids eat free" and free-attraction days</strong> — most cities have museums and zoos with free or pay-what-you-can hours.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The trip your kids remember isn't the expensive one.</strong> It's the one where you were relaxed, present, and not stressed about money the whole time. A cheap, well-planned trip beats an expensive, anxious one every time.</p>
        </div>

